No measured impact, but clearly raising of public awareness of of research into eye diseases in general and funding by the Medical Research Council for corneal graft rejection research in particular.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>Paper Presentation</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2010</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>A model of human corneal graft rejection in the NIH semi-inbred minipig was set up and evaluated, including ways of habituating pigs to personnel and clinical intervention. The model can be used for testing potential new treatments and is currently being used for basic genetic and immunological studies of clinical relevance.</gtr:description><gtr:id>3715EDCE-1DD1-49C3-8F4C-D298655ADAEF</gtr:id><gtr:impact>1. 3R-associated &amp;quot;Refinement&amp;quot; of animal use:
Development and evaluation of protocols to socialise pigs to research personnel before transplantation to minimise stress of essential peri-operative interventions and to maximise their success (see ref.1)
2. Novel observation that clinically accepted grafts that have never experienced a rejection episode may nevertheless contain cells of the immune system indicative of graft-specific immunity in the recipient (see ref. 2). Further investigation have been hampered by inability to recruit suitably qualified clinical or post-doctoral personnel. 
3. SNP analysis has permitted identification of possible minor histocompatibility loci responsible for immunological rejection. One locus contains the pig homologue of a gene shown previously to mediate rejection in mice, increasing the likelihood that a mismatch at this locus also mediates human corneal graft rejection. 
4. 3R-associated &amp;quot;Reduction&amp;quot; of animal use. SNP typing of potential graft donors and recipients in future will allow prediction of which minipigs will reject corneal grafts with an accuracy of 90% and to select donors and recipients accordingly, thereby reducing the number of animals used, e.g. in a therapeutic trial. 
5. The above capability will also enable early, pre-rejection immunological changes to be studied in relation to the predicted success or failure of a graft.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Pig model of corneal graft rejection</gtr:title><gtr:type>Model of mechanisms or symptoms - mammalian in vivo</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/15B6B820-C92F-41AD-A9A9-D390C2B77554"><gtr:id>15B6B820-C92F-41AD-A9A9-D390C2B77554</gtr:id><gtr:title>Perioperative socialization, care and monitoring of National Institutes of Health miniature swine undergoing ocular surgery and sampling of peripheral blood.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Laboratory animals</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/0315e7074b7db8f73aa544253cd66199"><gtr:id>0315e7074b7db8f73aa544253cd66199</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Nicholls SM</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0023-6772</gtr:issn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/A1E0B253-6D53-4174-B068-C437074AF906"><gtr:id>A1E0B253-6D53-4174-B068-C437074AF906</gtr:id><gtr:title>Genome-Wide Analysis in Swine Associates Corneal Graft Rejection with Donor-Recipient Mismatches in Three Novel Histocompatibility Regions and One Locus Homologous to the Mouse H-3 Locus.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>PloS one</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/900f15085684a59c8ecf7e8ff978e3d3"><gtr:id>900f15085684a59c8ecf7e8ff978e3d3</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Nicholls S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1932-6203</gtr:issn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http:/